This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with unsupervised word translation from non-parallel inter-lingual corpora. It also involves the use of neural network methods and adversarial loss functions, which are commonly used in natural language processing research. 

It could also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it involves the use of iterative matching methods and a novel linear method for alignment, which are machine learning techniques. 

Additionally, it could belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as it involves the use of unsupervised learning techniques for word translation. 

It could also belong to cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) as the iterative closest point method used in this paper is commonly used in computer vision for point cloud registration. 

Finally, it could belong to cs.IR (Information Retrieval) as it involves the alignment of word distributions between two languages, which is relevant to cross-lingual information retrieval.
